body.p:
Armed with this knowledge, the process of integrating the domain is as follows:
In myTopic.dtd, find the section DOMAIN ENTITY DECLARATIONS, and the declaration and reference for the last parameter entity in that section. Copy it and paste it immediately after the original:...
<!-- ============================================================= --> <!-- DOMAIN ENTITY DECLARATIONS --> <!-- ============================================================= --> ... <!ENTITY % xml-d-dec PUBLIC "-//OASIS//ENTITIES DITA 1.3 XML Domain//EN" "xmlDomain.ent" >%xml-d-dec;
<!ENTITY % xml-d-dec PUBLIC "-//OASIS//ENTITIES DITA 1.3 XML Domain//EN" "xmlDomain.ent" >%xml-d-dec;
...
In the copy, change xml-d-dec to dbPara-d-dec in both places where it occurs:<!ENTITY % dbPara-d-dec PUBLIC "-//OASIS//ENTITIES DITA 1.2 Highlight Domain//EN" "../../base/dtd/highlightDomain.ent" >%dbPara-d-dec;
Replace the public identifier string with the URN for the XML domain:<!ENTITY % dbPara-d-dec PUBLIC "urn:pubid:example.org:doctypes:dita:modules:dbPara:entities" "../../base/dtd/highlightDomain.ent" >%dbPara-d-dec;
Replace the system identifier with dbParaDomain.ent:<!ENTITY % dbPara-d-dec PUBLIC "urn:pubid:example.org:doctypes:dita:modules:xml:entities" "dbParaDomain.ent" >%dbPara-d-dec;
Find the comment DOMAIN EXTENSIONS and add a reference to the dbPara-d-keyword parameter entity to the declaration of the keyword parameter entity, then add a new entry for p, with the parameter entity for the dbPara-d-p:...
<!-- ============================================================= --> <!-- DOMAIN EXTENSIONS --> <!-- ============================================================= --> <!-- One for each extended base element, with the name of the domain(s) in which the extension was declared -->
<!ENTITY % pre "pre "> ... <!ENTITY % keyword "keyword | %markup-d-keyword; | %xml-d-keyword; | %dbPara-d-keyword; "> <!ENTITY % p "p | %dbPara-d-p; ">
...
Note the leading | character added after keyword in the original declaration. This parameter entity is used to build up an OR group of element type names, so you need to add the | (OR) connector between keyword and %dbPara-d-keyword;.If you forget the | character or accidentally leave one out you will get validation errors that may be cryptic or misleading, because they will often point to the declarations for elements somewhere deep in the DITA declaration sets, usually the first element type encountered that happens to use the parameter entity you just modified. When you get this type of error, the first thing to check is your domain extension parameter entitiesâ€”that is likely the cause of the error, especially if you are integrating pre-existing domains that you know are otherwise valid.
Find the comment DOMAINS ATTRIBUTE OVERRIDE and then the declaration for the included-domains text entity. Add a reference to the dbPara-d-att text entity:...
<!-- ============================================================= --> <!-- DOMAINS ATTRIBUTE OVERRIDE --> <!-- ============================================================= --> <!-- Must be declared ahead of the DTDs, which puts @domains first in order -->
<!ENTITY included-domains "&hi-d-att; &ut-d-att; &indexing-d-att; &abbrev-d-att; &xml-d-att; &dbPara-d-att; " >
...
Find section DOMAIN ELEMENT INTEGRATION and the last declaration and reference for a
parameter entity, probably xml-d-def. Copy it and paste a new copy immediately after the original:...
<!-- ============================================================= --> <!-- DOMAIN ELEMENT INTEGRATION --> <!-- ============================================================= -->
<!ENTITY % xml-d-def PUBLIC "-//OASIS//ELEMENTS DITA 1.3 XML Domain//EN" "xmlDomain.mod" >%xml-d-def;
<!ENTITY % xml-d-def PUBLIC "-//OASIS//ELEMENTS DITA 1.3 XML Domain//EN" "xmlDomain.mod" >%xml-d-def;
...
Change xml-d-def to dbPara-d-def everywhere it occurs:<!ENTITY % dbPara-d-def PUBLIC "-//OASIS//ELEMENTS DITA 1.2 Highlight Domain//EN" "../../base/dtd/highlightDomain.mod" >%dbPara-d-def;
Change the public identifier to the public ID for dbParaDomain.mod:<!ENTITY % dbPara-d-def PUBLIC "urn:pubid:example.org:doctypes:dita:modules:dbPara:declarations" "../../base/dtd/highlightDomain.mod" >%dbPara-d-def;If you are copying the public ID or URN from a catalog file, it is easy to accidentally copy the public ID for the .ent file instead of the .mod file and vice versa. If you get mysterious errors, like duplicate declaration messages or element type not declared messages even though you know you included the module, check the public ID value to make sure you didn't mix up the .ent and .mod public IDs.
Change the system identifier to dbParaDomain.mod:<!ENTITY % dbPara-d-def PUBLIC "urn:pubid:example.org:doctypes:dita:modules:dbPara:declarations" "dbParaDomain.mod" >%dbPara-d-def;
Validate your test document. Assuming that the XML domain module is already deployed (you can find it in the materials package for the tutorials), then your document should validate if you haven't made any syntax errors in the shell DTD.
If the document validates, see if you can enter any of the element types from the domain, such as xmlelem or xmlatt, into a paragraph. You should be able to.
